<h1>Installing NovaSheets</h1>
<p>
    NovaSheets is installed simply by embedding a JavaScript file into your HTML.
    This file can be downloaded and hosted locally by you
    (see <a href="#downloading">ยง&nbsp;Downloading</a>)
    or you can link directly to the source code
    (see <a href="#importing">ยง&nbsp;Importing</a>).
    That's it!
</p>

<h2 id="downloading">Downloading</h2>
<p>
    See the <a href="/versions/">Versions</a> page to choose a version to download.
    Once you have done this, you can download one of the files given and add them to your project,
    or embed NovaSheets into your project directly using the code provided.
</p>

<h2 id="importing">Importing</h2>
<p>
    The latest version is <strong>{% include "templates/version.txt" %}</strong>
    and can be imported using the code below:
    <pre>
        &lt;script src="https://novasheets.netlify.app/src/{% include "templates/version.txt" %}/min">&lt;/script>
    </pre>
</p>

<p>
    While the minified version above is recommended for general use, you can also choose to use the more verbose regular version, which includes comments and the like:
    <pre>
        &lt;script src="https://novasheets.netlify.app/src/{% include "templates/version.txt" %}">&lt;/script>
    </pre>
</p>

<p>
    Alternatively, you can choose to import the main live source code directly,
    but be warned that it is continually updated and may contain incomplete or buggy features,
    so use it at your own risk:
    <pre>
        &lt;script src="https://novasheets.netlify.app/src/latest">&lt;/script>
    </pre>
</p>

<h2 id="browser-support">Browser support</h1>
<p>
    NovaSheets is supported in all major browsers, including Chrome, Edge (Chromium), Firefox, Opera, and Safari.
    NovaSheets does not work in Internet Explorer, as it is written using the following features from <a href="https://www.w3schools.com/js/js_es6.asp">ECMAScript 6 (2015)</a>:

    <ul>
        <li>Arrow functions (<code>=></code>)</li>
        <li>
            <code>let</code> and <code>const</code> declarations</li>
        <li>Rest operator (<code>...</code>)</li>
        <li>RegEx negative lookbehinds <code>(?&lt;!.)</code> and <code>(?&lt;=.)</code></li>
    </ul>
</p>